insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('anthony-joshua-vs-daniel-dubois', 'Joshua vs Dubois: two of the division''s heaviest hands, and the question of who blinks first', 'Between them, Anthony Joshua and Daniel Dubois have stopped 48 opponents. This is not a fight that promises to go the distance. It promises to find a chin.', '<p>Put their numbers side by side and the picture is almost comic. Between them, Anthony Joshua and Daniel Dubois have won 52 fights and ended 48 of them early. This is not a contest built for the judges. It is a meeting of two of the heaviest hands at heavyweight, and the only real question is whose chin answers first.</p>

<h2>Power on both sides</h2>
<p>Dubois carries the more frightening rate. Of his 23 wins, 22 have come inside the distance, a knockout ratio of 96 per cent. Opponents are rarely still upright to hear a verdict. Joshua is not far behind. He has stopped 26 of his 29 victims, 90 per cent, and only three of his wins have ever reached the cards. Neither man is built to win dull decisions, and neither has had to learn how.</p>

<h2>The other side of the ledger</h2>
<p>Both also know what the canvas looks like. Joshua''s record carries four defeats and Dubois''s three, and the last five fights for each contain a knockout loss. These are not protected prospects. They are established heavyweights who hit hard, have been hurt, and keep coming forward. That shared vulnerability is what makes the fight live. There is no safe man here.</p>

<h2>The physical edge</h2>
<p>Joshua is the bigger figure on paper, 6ft 6in to Dubois''s 6ft 5in, with an 82-inch reach against 78. Four inches of reach matters at this weight if he chooses to box behind the jab rather than trade. Dubois has youth on his side of the same orthodox stance, eight years of it, at 28 to Joshua''s 36.</p>

<h2>Where it turns</h2>
<p>The data points to one clean fork. If Joshua uses his length and keeps Dubois at the end of his punches, the experience of 33 professional contests should tell. If the fight is fought up close, where a 96 per cent and a 90 per cent knockout rate collide, it becomes a test of who recovers. Recent results suggest either man can be the one who does not.</p>', ARRAY['Anthony Joshua', 'Daniel Dubois', 'heavyweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('canelo-alvarez-vs-christian-m-billi', 'Who is Christian M''billi? The unbeaten puncher across from Canelo Álvarez', 'Canelo Álvarez is one of the most recognisable names in boxing, but the more intriguing question in this super-middleweight title bout is the man opposite him. Here is what the numbers say about Christian M''billi.', '<p>When a fight involves Canelo Álvarez, the famous name takes care of itself. The reason to look closer at this super-middleweight title bout, reported to have moved to late October, is the man in the other corner. Christian M''billi arrives unbeaten, younger and barely known to the wider audience, and the numbers make him worth understanding.</p>

<h2>Christian M''billi, the unbeaten challenger</h2>
<p>M''billi''s record stands at 29-0-1. What stands out is how he gets there. Of his 29 wins, 24 have come by knockout, and only five have gone to the judges'' scorecards. This is a fighter built around finishing rather than out-pointing opponents. The single mark against him is a draw. He has yet to be beaten as a professional.</p>
<p>At 31 he is four years the younger man, and his 72-inch reach makes him the longer fighter in the ring even though the pair stand the same 5ft 8in. His recent outings fit the punching profile. Across his last five he has mixed stoppages with decisions, two of those wins ending early. For a relative unknown stepping up to this level, a career spent ending fights is the headline an audience needs.</p>

<h2>Canelo Álvarez, the established name</h2>
<p>Álvarez is the known quantity. At 35 his 63-3-2 record spans 68 professional contests, with 39 wins inside the distance and 24 on the cards. He is as comfortable banking rounds as forcing a stoppage. Recent form has leaned on his judgement, a run of decision wins that suggests a boxer increasingly content to control fights rather than chase the knockout.</p>

<h2>How they match up</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Experience:</strong> Álvarez has been 68 professional contests deep, M''billi 30. That is the widest gap on the page.</li>
<li><strong>Finishing:</strong> M''billi stops opponents far more often, roughly 83 per cent of his wins by knockout against Álvarez''s 62.</li>
<li><strong>Going the distance:</strong> Álvarez has 24 decision wins to M''billi''s five, the clearer sign of a fighter proven over twelve hard rounds.</li>
<li><strong>Reach:</strong> M''billi''s 72 inches to Álvarez''s 70 gives the challenger a two-inch edge in length, despite the two men sharing the same listed height.</li>
<li><strong>Age:</strong> M''billi is 31 to Álvarez''s 35.</li>
</ul>
<p>Both men are orthodox, so this is not a clash of contrasting styles on paper. It is a younger, longer, heavier-handed challenger set against experience and ring-craft.</p>

<h2>What to watch</h2>
<p>The interesting battle is stylistic. M''billi will want to use that reach and his finishing pressure on an opponent who has rarely been overwhelmed. Álvarez, increasingly a points fighter, will look to drag a younger, longer man into the deep rounds where M''billi has spent comparatively little time. That trade, finishing power and length against accumulated experience, is the fight.</p>', ARRAY['Christian M''billi', 'Canelo Álvarez', 'super middleweight', 'fight preview', 'world title', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('chantelle-cameron-vs-natasha-jonas', 'Cameron vs Jonas: a points master against a veteran southpaw', 'This super-welterweight meeting is a clash of methods. Chantelle Cameron''s relentless scorecard boxing against the awkward, heavier-handed southpaw work of Natasha Jonas.', '<p>This is a fight about how you win, not only whether you do. Chantelle Cameron has built a 21-1 record largely on the cards. Thirteen of her wins have gone to a decision and only eight have ended early, a knockout rate of 38 per cent. She wins rounds, banks them, and rarely needs the referee. Natasha Jonas offers something different in almost every respect.</p>

<h2>Cameron: volume and the scorecards</h2>
<p>At 35, Cameron arrives on a four-fight winning run, every one of them a decision. That is a fighter in rhythm, doing exactly what she does best. The low stoppage rate is part of her identity rather than a flaw in it. She is content to make a fight long and pile up the rounds, trusting her output to be there at the final bell.</p>

<h2>Jonas: the southpaw veteran</h2>
<p>Jonas, at 42, is the older fighter by seven years and the only southpaw in the ring. Her 16-3-1 record carries a higher finishing rate, nine knockouts at 56 per cent, and the stance alone changes the geometry. Orthodox against southpaw is the first puzzle both corners have to solve. Her recent five is more varied than Cameron''s clean run, with a stoppage win in there but also a defeat.</p>

<h2>What decides it</h2>
<p>Can Jonas''s southpaw angles and heavier hands disrupt a fighter who is happy to make it long? Long is precisely where Cameron''s points pedigree lives. The shared height of 5ft 8in means neither can simply box over the top of the other. This one is settled in the exchanges and the accumulation, not the silhouette.</p>', ARRAY['Chantelle Cameron', 'Natasha Jonas', 'super welterweight', 'women''s boxing', 'fight preview']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('hamzah-sheeraz-vs-chris-eubank-jr', 'Sheeraz vs Eubank Jr: a rising super-middleweight meets a fraying name', 'Chris Eubank Jr is the bigger name and, at 36, the more vulnerable one. Hamzah Sheeraz is younger, unbeaten and a good deal bigger. This has the shape of a changing of the guard.', '<p>Chris Eubank Jr is the bigger name here and, at 36, the more vulnerable one. Hamzah Sheeraz is 27, unbeaten, and a good deal bigger physically. This super-middleweight meeting has the shape of a changing of the guard, provided the younger man is as ready as his record suggests.</p>

<h2>Sheeraz: unbeaten, and the longer fighter</h2>
<p>Sheeraz arrives 23-0-1 with 19 knockouts, an 83 per cent finishing rate, and a recent five made up almost entirely of stoppages. At 6ft 3in with a 75-inch reach he is the rangier man by a clear margin, the kind of tall, heavy-handed boxer who can fight at distance and still hurt you.</p>

<h2>Eubank Jr: experience, and a record that has started to fray</h2>
<p>Eubank''s case is mileage. His 35-4 record spans 39 professional contests, with 25 knockouts at 71 per cent and 10 decisions, the deep résumé of a fighter who has shared rings with serious operators. His recent five carries both a decision loss and a knockout loss. The experience is real, and so is the wear that has begun to show alongside it.</p>

<h2>Size and youth against the name</h2>
<p>Sheeraz is four inches taller, three longer in reach, nine years younger and still unbeaten. Eubank brings 39 fights and an awkward durability that has troubled better-credentialled opponents. That experience has to offset a younger, longer, fresher man. On the evidence of his last few outings, the most telling line on the page may be the recent stoppage against Eubank''s name.</p>', ARRAY['Hamzah Sheeraz', 'Chris Eubank Jr', 'super middleweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('jack-catterall-vs-adam-azim', 'Adam Azim''s biggest test: Jack Catterall and the step into championship water', 'Adam Azim is 23, unbeaten and finishing everyone in front of him. Jack Catterall is exactly the kind of seasoned southpaw who tends to slow that sort of hurry down.', '<p>Adam Azim has rarely had to find out what the later rounds feel like. Fifteen fights, fifteen wins, twelve by knockout, and his last five have all ended early. At 23 he has the look of a fighter the sport is in a hurry to crown. Jack Catterall is the opponent who tends to put a stop to that kind of momentum.</p>

<h2>The unbeaten 23-year-old</h2>
<p>Azim''s profile is power and pace. He carries an 80 per cent knockout rate and a five-fight run of stoppages, the form of a young man walking through the level beneath him. He is the taller fighter here too, 5ft 11in against Catterall''s 5ft 7in, and he works from an orthodox stance. What the record cannot yet show is how he behaves when an opponent is still there in the championship rounds.</p>

<h2>The man sent to ask the questions</h2>
<p>Catterall, 32, brings 33-2 over a far longer career and an opposite way of winning. Nineteen of his victories have come on the cards, his knockout rate sits at 42 per cent, and his southpaw style has carried him through hard, deep fights and back from a disputed defeat. He has lived in the rounds Azim has mostly skipped.</p>

<h2>Youth and power against the miles</h2>
<p>The contrasts are clean. Nine years, four inches of height, and a stance switch from orthodox to southpaw that complicates the range for both men. Azim has to prove his finishing carries into deeper water against someone comfortable there. Catterall, at 32, has to make a 23-year-old work long enough to find that out. Whoever imposes his preferred pace tends to win this kind of fight.</p>', ARRAY['Adam Azim', 'Jack Catterall', 'super lightweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('joshua-buatsi-vs-anthony-yarde', 'Buatsi vs Yarde: Britain''s light-heavyweight reckoning, and a clash of methods', 'One has a 27-fight knockout habit and a record that swings. The other has lost just once and tends to win on the cards. British light-heavyweight has waited a while for this.', '<p>British light-heavyweight has waited a long time to put Joshua Buatsi and Anthony Yarde in the same ring. The appeal is in the mismatch of methods. These are two good fighters who arrive at the same place by opposite routes.</p>

<h2>Yarde: the finisher who lives dangerously</h2>
<p>Yarde''s 27-4 record is built on power. He has stopped 24 opponents, an 89 per cent knockout rate that places him among the heavier hitters in the division. The cost of that style sits right next to it: four defeats, and a recent five that opens with a knockout loss. When Yarde is in a fight, it tends to be a real one, settled by who lands rather than who out-points.</p>

<h2>Buatsi: quieter, and harder to catch</h2>
<p>Buatsi wins with less drama. His 20-1 record includes 13 knockouts at a 65 per cent clip but also seven decisions, and his recent form is a steady accumulation of points wins rather than highlight finishes. He is the bigger man too, 6ft 2in to Yarde''s 6ft, with a two-inch reach advantage to keep range with.</p>

<h2>Power against control</h2>
<p>This is a puncher with one clear defeat against a boxer with one clear defeat. It turns on whether Yarde''s power finds the chin before Buatsi''s length and control quietly bank the rounds. The records say Yarde is the more likely to end it early, and also the more likely to be ended.</p>', ARRAY['Joshua Buatsi', 'Anthony Yarde', 'light heavyweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('moses-itauma-vs-fabio-wardley', 'Moses Itauma is 21. Fabio Wardley is the test that tells us how real he is.', 'Fourteen fights, fourteen wins, a five-fight knockout streak, and Moses Itauma is only 21. Fabio Wardley is the first opponent built to find out what is underneath the hype.', '<p>Moses Itauma is 21 years old, and that single fact reframes everything else on his record. Fourteen fights, fourteen wins, twelve by knockout, and a last five that reads as five straight stoppages. Plenty of heavyweights spend their early twenties learning the trade. Itauma has spent his ending nights early. Fabio Wardley is the first opponent built to find out what sits beneath that.</p>

<h2>The prospect</h2>
<p>Itauma''s appeal is in the package. An 86 per cent knockout rate, a southpaw stance and a 79-inch reach make him an awkward, heavy-handed problem at 6ft 4in. The caveat is just as plain. Fourteen professional fights is a short education, and none of them has forced him into the deep, ugly rounds that define the division.</p>

<h2>The proven puncher</h2>
<p>Wardley, 31, is the more battle-tested article. His 20-1-1 record carries 19 knockouts, a 95 per cent finishing rate of his own. His recent five tells a rawer story than Itauma''s tidy run, taking in a knockout loss, a sequence of stoppage wins and a draw. He has lived in the chaotic, momentum-swinging rounds that the younger man''s record has never required.</p>

<h2>What we actually learn</h2>
<p>This is an audition with real stakes. Itauma brings the southpaw stance, a marginal reach edge and a decade of youth, since Wardley is ten years older. Wardley brings scars and the hard-won knowledge of what to do when a fight stops going to plan. Both can clearly punch. What nobody has seen yet is how Itauma reacts the first time a night refuses to go his way, and Wardley is built to ask exactly that.</p>', ARRAY['Moses Itauma', 'Fabio Wardley', 'heavyweight', 'prospect', 'fight preview']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('nick-ball-vs-leigh-wood', 'Nick Ball gives away five inches to Leigh Wood, and that''s rather the point', 'Nick Ball is 5ft 2in, Leigh Wood 5ft 7in. For Ball, the height gap is not a problem to solve. It is the whole engine of how he fights.', '<p>Nick Ball stands 5ft 2in. Leigh Wood stands 5ft 7in. In most sports a five-inch gap would settle an argument before it began. In Ball''s case it powers the way he fights. This featherweight meeting is a study in what a small, relentless pressure fighter does to a taller, rangier opponent.</p>

<h2>Ball: small, and always coming forward</h2>
<p>Ball''s 23-1-1 record splits the difference between pressure and craft. He has 13 knockouts at 57 per cent, but also 10 wins on the cards, so the volume he throws does not come at the expense of being able to box. At 29, with a 65-inch reach, he has spent his career closing the distance that taller men want to keep. It is the only way a fighter his size survives, and he has turned it into a weapon.</p>

<h2>Wood: the taller veteran with a dramatic past</h2>
<p>Wood, 37, brings 29-4 and a near-identical finishing profile, 17 knockouts at 59 per cent plus 12 decisions. The warning sign is in his recent five, which contains two knockout losses. He has been in thrillers, and more than once he has been caught. He is eight years older than Ball and gives up nothing in reach, standing five inches taller.</p>

<h2>Range against pressure</h2>
<p>The fight frames itself. If Wood can use those five inches of height to keep Ball at the end of his punches, his experience over 33 contests should tell. If Ball gets underneath that range and turns it into a phone-box fight, the taller man''s recent habit of being stopped moves to the centre of the story.</p>', ARRAY['Nick Ball', 'Leigh Wood', 'featherweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;
insert into articles (slug, title, summary, body, tags, ai_generated) values ('richard-riakporhe-vs-chris-billam-smith', 'Riakporhe vs Billam-Smith: the puncher and the points machine at cruiserweight', 'Two routes to the same elite level meet at cruiserweight. Richard Riakporhe ends fights. Chris Billam-Smith wins them in instalments.', '<p>At cruiserweight, two opposite ways of reaching the same level collide. Richard Riakporhe ends fights. Chris Billam-Smith wins them in instalments. Their records sit close together in quality and a long way apart in character, which is what makes the matchup worth a look.</p>

<h2>Riakporhe: power, and a single defeat</h2>
<p>Riakporhe''s 20-1 ledger is the heavier one. He has 16 knockouts, an 80 per cent finishing rate, and a recent five built around a three-fight stoppage streak. At 6ft 5in and 36 years old he is the bigger man in the ring and the one more likely to make the scorecards irrelevant.</p>

<h2>Billam-Smith: output and the deep rounds</h2>
<p>Billam-Smith, 35, gets there differently. His 22-2 record leans on activity. He has 14 knockouts at 64 per cent, plus eight wins on the cards and a recent run of decision victories that speaks to a fighter comfortable working twelve hard rounds. Where Riakporhe looks to shorten a fight, Billam-Smith is happy to let it run and out-work you in it.</p>

<h2>How it splits</h2>
<p>Two inches of height favour Riakporhe, and the power clearly does. Billam-Smith''s counter is volume and his ease in the championship rounds. Does Riakporhe''s power land before the busier man piles up the rounds, or does Billam-Smith drag the puncher somewhere he would rather not go? On the numbers, that is the fight worth tuning in for.</p>', ARRAY['Richard Riakporhe', 'Chris Billam-Smith', 'cruiserweight', 'fight preview', 'boxing']::text[], true)
on conflict (slug) do update set title=excluded.title, summary=excluded.summary, body=excluded.body, tags=excluded.tags, ai_generated=excluded.ai_generated;

